## Introduction

In Lab 0, you built a stopwatch using a bare-metal `while(true)` loop with `elapsedMillis` timers. That approach works for simple programs, but it has fundamental limitations:

- Every task shares one loop — if the display takes too long, buttons feel sluggish.
- Adding features means more `if` checks, more state variables, and more coupling.
- There is no way to guarantee that a time-critical operation runs on schedule.

In this lab, you will **redesign your stopwatch from the ground up** using FreeRTOS. You already know _what_ the stopwatch should do. Now you must figure out _how to decompose it into concurrent tasks_ that cooperate through RTOS primitives.

<Aside type="caution" title="No Starter Code">
There is no template for this lab. You will create a new CCS project, integrate FreeRTOS yourself, and write all application code. Your Lab 0 code is your reference — not your starting point.
</Aside>

---

## Objectives

By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

- Set up a FreeRTOS project from scratch in Code Composer Studio
- Decompose a system into concurrent tasks with defined responsibilities
- Assign task priorities based on timing requirements
- Use `vTaskDelay` and `vTaskDelayUntil` for periodic scheduling
- Communicate between tasks using **queues**
- Identify and handle shared state between concurrent tasks

---

